occurrenceRemarks: Heuchera villosa foliage on Grandfather Mountain. You can tell why this plant is also called mapleleaf alumroot - the lobed and palmately veined leaves resemble maple leaves.

Hairy alumroot flowering on top of Grandfather Mountain. They like rocky places and often root in crevices along shaded ledges and cliffs. The flowers are tiny but certainly were doing their job in attracting pollinators. The bees I saw on it had collected bright red pollen matching the color of the anthers on these plants.
Close-up of the tiny flowers of Heuchera villosa on top of Grandfather Mountain.

occurrenceRemarks: Not confident in species. Several plants growing in shade on boulders at base of (somewhat calcareous?) rock outcropping in rich woods. They didn't look like H. americana, the only species of this genus I am familiar with in the wild. H. americana was already in bloom elsewhere in the park; this plant did not yet have any flower stalks visible, thus I assume it will bloom later. Pretty sure no one calls this plant "crag-jangle"" but its a great name, I must admit."
